    "preview_source": "tier7-ingest-v0.2",
    "summary": "CD7 is aberrantly expressed in up to one third of Acute Myeloid Leukaemia (AML) patients, in which it is associated with lower rates of complete remission, greater incidence of relapse and poorer survival. However, the functional role of CD7 in AML pathogenesis remains largely unexplored. This thesis aimed to characterise the biological function of CD7 and evaluate its potential as a therapeutic target in AML. Analysis of AML patient datasets confirmed that high levels of CD7 expression are associated with poorer survival, disease immaturity and higher-risk genetic profiles. Proteomic analysis of primary AML samples revealed that CD7 is frequently co-expressed with leukaemic stem cell (LSC) markers CD34 and CD123, validating the immature phenotype of CD7+ AML. Transcriptomic analysis of CD"
